    "verdict": {
        "winner": "A Court of Thorns and Roses",
        "summary": "A Court of Thorns and Roses wins decisively with 1.25 million ratings at 4.3 stars versus Shatter Me's 685,000 ratings at 4.1 stars. ACOTAR has richer world-building (Seven Courts, mating bonds, Under the Mountain trials) and a series that improves with each book—ACOMAF is considered even better than book 1. Shatter Me has innovative prose with strikethrough text and a complete series, but the dystopian world-building is thin and the writing style aggressively polarizes readers. Different genres (high fantasy fae romance vs YA dystopian romance), but ACOTAR is the safer bet for most readers.",
        "recommendation": "Read A Court of Thorns and Roses first if you want the fantasy romance that sparked the entire 'romantasy' BookTok trend. Yes, the first 200 pages are slow, but the Under the Mountain trials (chapters 35-47) are brutal and gripping—Feyre faces the Middengard Wyrm, solves riddles under torture, kills innocents to save Tamlin. The mating bond concept, Seven Courts world-building, and Rhysand's reveal in book 2 are genre-defining. Book 2 (A Court of Mist and Fury) has 1.1 million ratings at 4.6 stars and is widely considered superior to book 1—rare for a series. You're investing in 5 books and 3,000+ pages, but the payoff is enormous. THEN read Shatter Me if you loved the romance but want something shorter and stylistically unique. Mafi's strikethrough text ('I'm a monster a creature a mistake'), Warner's villain-to-hero arc, and Juliette's lethal touch power are distinctive. The prose is purple and poetic—you'll either devour it or DNF at chapter 3. Stop after book 3 (Ignite Me) when the trilogy concludes; books 4-6 are unnecessary. If you only read one, choose ACOTAR—it has double the readership, better world-building, and a series that builds momentum instead of declining. But if you hate slow burns and want something you can finish in a weekend, Shatter Me's 338 pages vs ACOTAR's 419 pages makes it the quicker choice. Just know the dystopian setting is window dressing for the romance."
